{"CoRequisites": [], "CreditType": "", "Credits": "4.00", "CrossListed": "Y", "DepartmentID": "43,46", "Departments": "EN Applied Mathematics & Statistics, EN Biomedical Engineering", "Description": "Computational systems biology has emerged as the dominant framework for analyzing high-dimensional “omics” data in order to uncover the relationships among molecules, networks and disease.  In particular, many of the core methodologies are based on statistical modeling, including machine learning, stochastic processes and statistical inference. We will cover the key aspects of this methodology, including measuring associations, testing multiple hypotheses, and learning predictors, Markov chains and graphical models. In addition, by studying recent important articles in cancer systems biology, we will illustrate how this approach enhances our ability to annotate genomes, discover molecular disease networks, detect disease, predict clinical outcomes, and characterize disease progression. Whereas a good foundation in probability and statistics is necessary, no prior exposure to molecular biology is required (although helpful).", "Equivalencies": [], "EvaluationUrls": [], "Fees": [], "GradeSystemName": "AE Ugrad Letter", "InstructionMethods": "In-person", "Instructors": [{"HopkinsID": "GZ0X1K|GZ0X1K"}], "Meetings": [{"Building": "Hodson", "DOW": "MW", "Dates": "01-23-2023 to 04-28-2023", "Format": "Lecture", "Times": "01:30 PM - 02:45 PM"}, {"Building": "Hodson", "DOW": "F", "Dates": "01-23-2023 to 04-28-2023", "Format": "Discussion Section", "Times": "10:00 AM - 10:50 AM"}], "PosTags": [{"Tag": "BMED-BDS"}, {"Tag": "BME-CM"}, {"Tag": "BMED-GSB"}, {"Tag": "CSCI-OTHER"}, {"Tag": "BME-GSB"}], "PrereqCoursesCatalogs": [{"Description": "Computational systems biology has emerged as the dominant framework for analyzing high-dimensional “omics” data in order to uncover the relationships among molecules, networks and disease.  In particular, many of the core methodologies are based on statistical modeling, including machine learning, stochastic processes and statistical inference. We will cover the key aspects of this methodology, including measuring associations, testing multiple hypotheses, and learning predictors, Markov chains and graphical models. In addition, by studying recent important articles in cancer systems biology, we will illustrate how this approach enhances our ability to annotate genomes, discover molecular disease networks, detect disease, predict clinical outcomes, and characterize disease progression. Whereas a good foundation in probability and statistics is necessary, no prior exposure to molecular biology is required (although helpful).  Recommended Course Background: EN.553.620 AND EN.553.630.", "Name": "EN.553.650", "SssCoursesId": 39624, "StatusName": "Active", "TermName": "AE Spring 2023", "Title": "Computational Molecular Medicine"}, {"Description": "Probability and its applications, at the calculus level. Emphasis on techniques of application and on rigorous mathematical demonstration.  Probability, combinatorial probability, random variables, distribution functions, important probability distributions, independence, conditional probability, moments, covariance and correlation, limit theorems.  Students initiating graduate work in probability or statistics should enroll in EN.553.620 or EN.553.720.  Prerequisites: one year of calculus.  Corequisites: multivariable calculus and linear algebra.

Students who have received credit for AS.110.106 and/or AS.110.107 taken prior to Fall 2020 should contact the course instructor to determine whether they can receive permission to register for this course.", "Name": "EN.553.420", "SssCoursesId": 39352, "StatusName": "Active", "TermName": "AE Spring 2023", "Title": "Probability"}, {"Description": "Probability and its applications, at the calculus level. Emphasis on techniques of application and on rigorous mathematical demonstration. Probability, combinatorial probability, random variables, distribution functions, important probability distributions, independence, conditional probability, moments, exchangeability, joint distributions, conditional distributions and expectation, covariance and correlation, limit theorems.  The honors version of this course will have enrichment exercises that explore and extend ideas learned in the ordinary lecture.  Students initiating graduate work in probability or statistics should enroll in EN.550.620. Auditors are not permitted. Recommended Course Background: one year of calculus and mathematical maturity; Co-requisite: multivariable calculus. 
By permission of the instructor or by recommendation of an AMS faculty member.", "Name": "EN.553.421", "SssCoursesId": 44541, "StatusName": "Active", "TermName": "AE Spring 2023", "Title": "Honors Probability"}, {"Description": "Probability and its applications, at the calculus level. Emphasis on techniques of application and on rigorous mathematical demonstration. Probability, combinatorial probability, random variables, distribution functions, important probability distributions, independence, conditional probability, moments, covariance and correlation, limit theorems.  Recommended course background: (AS.110.109 or  AS.110.113) and previously or concurrently (AS.110.202 or AS.110.201 or AS.110.212).", "Name": "EN.553.620", "SssCoursesId": 39380, "StatusName": "Active", "TermName": "AE Spring 2023", "Title": "Probability"}, {"Description": "Introduction to mathematical statistics. Finite population sampling, approximation methods,classical parametric estimation, hypothesis testing, analysis of variance, and regression. Bayesian methods.", "Name": "EN.553.430", "SssCoursesId": 39356, "StatusName": "Active", "TermName": "AE Spring 2023", "Title": "Mathematical Statistics"}, {"Description": "Introduction to the theory and methodology of mathematical statistics: parametric estimation, including asymptotic properties of estimators and approximation methods; hypothesis testing; analysis of variance; regression; bootstrapping and nonparametrics. Intended for students with a particular interest in the theoretical foundations of statistical procedures.", "Name": "EN.553.431", "SssCoursesId": 42974, "StatusName": "Active", "TermName": "AE Spring 2023", "Title": "Honors Mathematical Statistics"}, {"Description": "Introduction to the basic principles of mathematical statistics and data analysis. Emphasis on techniques of application. Classical parametric estimation, hypothesis testing, and multiple decision problems; linear models, analysis of variance, and regression; nonparametric and robust procedures; decision-theoretic setting, Bayesian methods. Recommended Course Background: EN.553.620 AND ( AS.110.201 OR AS.110.212 OR EN.553.291 ).", "Name": "EN.553.630", "SssCoursesId": 39383, "StatusName": "Active", "TermName": "AE Spring 2023", "Title": "Mathematical Statistics"}], "Prerequisites": [{"Description": "Students may receive credit for EN.553.450 or EN.553.650, but not both.", "Expression": "EN.553.650[C]", "IsNegative": "Y"}, {"Description": "(EN.553.420 OR EN.553.421 OR EN.553.620) AND ( EN.553.430 OR EN.553.431 OR EN.553.630) OR equivalent courses in probability and statistics.", "Expression": "(^EN.553.420[C]^OR^EN.553.421[C]^OR^EN.553.620[C]^)^AND^(^EN.553.430[C]^OR^EN.553.431[C]^OR^EN.553.630[C]^)", "IsNegative": "N"}], "Restrictions": [{"Description": "", "RestrictionName": "ASEN Undergraduate Students only"}], "SampleSyllabus": "", "SectionCoReqNotes": "", "SectionCoRequisites": "", "StandardSyllabusLink": "", "TextbookInformations": [{"AttributeValue": "Barnes & Noble", "BookstoreID": "", "ClassStartDate": "20230123", "CourseName": "EN.553.450", "CourseNumber": "", "Department": "", "IdrGroupTerm": "W23", "Location": "Homewood Campus", "MbsGroupDesignator": "", "MbsSiteCode": "", "Name": "01", "SectionNumber": "", "Term": "", "ZonesName": "ASEN - UGrad"}], "WebNotes": "Enrollment restricted to AMS majors for two weeks. Open to undergraduates only after two weeks."}
